                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/612: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-13T23:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 13, 1936—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 13—11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. For Davis, London. My 10, January 13, 6 p.m.<note n="20" xml:id="d26fn20">Not
                        printed.</note> Hirota<note n="21" xml:id="d26fn21">Koki Hirota, Japanese
                        Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> tonight confirmed to me personally and
                    definitely that he had won out in his contest with the Navy over immediate
                    withdrawal of the Japanese delegation from London. He said that while Admiral
                    Nagano might return to Tokyo he hoped and expected that Ambassador Nagai<note
                        n="22" xml:id="d26fn22">Matsuzo Nagai, Japanese Ambassador in the United
                        Kingdom and delegate to the Naval Conference.</note> would remain in the
                    Conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
